{
  "texts": [
    "We define the pair-encoding map φ: {0, 1} → {0, 1} 2, φ(0) = 10, φ(1) = 01 and extend φ to a map ϕ: {0, 1} n → {0, 1} 2n by applying it coordinatewise: forg n = b 1 b 2 • • • b n ∈ {0, 1} n, b j ∈ {0, 1}, let ϕ(g n) = φ(b 1) φ(b 2) • • • φ(b n).For n ∈ N, we then can define the set H 2n = (h 2n 0, h 2n 1,..., h 2n 2 n -1) and H 2n-1 = (π(h 2n 0), π(h 2n 1),..., π(h 2n 2 n -1)), where h 2n i:= ϕ(g n i) ∈ {0, 1} 2n and π: {0, 1} 2n → {0, 1} 2n-1 be the projection that deletes the last coordinate: π(x 1,..., x 2n) = (x 1,..., x 2n-1).By construction, the family {H n } forms a collection of 2-Gray codes, and any two consecutive codewords h n i and h n i+1satisfy d H (h n i, h n i+1) ≤ 2.In our paper, a tree of depth N stores the sequence {H n } 2N n=1, and each rank bin corresponds to a distinct h 2N i or π(h 2N i).",
    "Compared with using a standard 1-Gray code, this construction has the advantage of slowing the growth rate of rank bins as the number of table columns increases, since|H n | = 2 ⌈n/2⌉ whereas |G n | = 2 n.This reduction leads to greater robustness of bit retrieval against rank shifts.",
    "In Appendix G.1, we provide additional evaluations on using a 1-Gray code for bit sequence generation.",
    "D Missing Details from Section 3Soundness of robustness analysis in the transformed domain.",
    "Our theoretical analysis is conducted entirely in the transformed domain, where both the original data X and the watermarked data X wm have already been processed using the Yeo-Johnson transformation (YJT) and standardization."
  ]
}